Sep 22 2008 	The Greatest Beds in Europe!	Our family of six (which included two 20-year-old girls, a 16-year-old boy and a 13-year old daughter) had two triple rooms at Hart House Hotel. Two months later, we're still talking wistfully about those beds! They are wonderful! Our group had two triple rooms. We were prepared for a long climb to third-floor rooms (as warned in other reviews). Instead, we were pleasantly surprised to have two first-floor triple rooms. The rooms were pleasant with high ceilings and ample space for three to move around. We didn't have air conditioning, but the rooms were pre-equipped with fans. Frankly, even in July, London's weather was cool enough that we didn't even need them.  The location is great and the neighborhood has charm. The hop-on-hop-off bus even goes down the street passing the hotel with commentary on the history of the street's buildings. Everything is in easy walking distance. We never felt unsafe, and we walked in the neighborhood day and even late at night. After we learned the lay of the land, we allowed our teenagers to walk around together without us and they were fine. Staff was pleasant and very efficient. We are also the type to throw our luggage in a room and to be out sightseeing day and night. At first, we had difficulty getting directions from desk staff since the (very nice) woman working the desk wasn't English and there was a language barrier. She didn't know common landmarks and sites, so couldn't give us a hint on which direction to go. We ended up grabbing a couple maps and finding our way everywhere, so it wasn't a big deal. On the other hand, when we needed something, she (and other staff) were extremely efficient and responded immediately. We would definately stay here again and recommend it highly. It's a pleasant and cozy surprise in busy London!	
Jan 4 2008 	Good value for London	Stayed overnight in this hotel located in Marylebone (roughly between Baker Street and Oxford Street). I had a single room and expected the worst. You have to ring the door bell and wait for someone to come to the door to open it for you. Someone came promptly and asked who I was and went to get the key. I was then told how to get to my room.I was pleasantly surprised. There were 3 flights of stairs to the room so I would not recommend you go there with heavy luggage but the room was quite large for a single room. The bed was what I would call a small double, there was a wardrobe, desk/make up table, a stool for the desk and an armchair. There was a small kettle to make tea/coffee. The small ensuite bathroom had no natural light but was good enough for an overnight stay. It has a small shower, loo and washbasin. Towels were nice and fluffy. Everything was immaculately clean.Breakfast was in the basement. Tables were already laid with plates/cutlery and orange juice. You could help yourself to the usual range of cereals and some fresh fruits. A range of cooked breakfast was available (the scrambled eggs and toast I had were fine) and there was jam and marmelade at the table. The staff were pleasant throughout. The ony problem I had was with the road noise - my room was overlooking the main road - I guess it is difficult to get away from road noise in London! So if you want peace and quiet, I would recommend you ask for a room at the back.	
